[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] In computing, an **effect system** is a formal system that describes the computational effects of computer programs, such as side effects.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] An effect system can be used to provide a compile-time check of the possible effects of the program.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] The effect system extends the notion of type to have an "effect" component, which comprises an **effect kind** and a **region**.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] The effect kind describes *what* is being done, and the region describes *with what* (parameters) it is being done.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] An effect system is typically an extension of a type system.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] The term "**type and effect system**" is sometimes used in this case.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] Often, a type of a value is denoted together with its effect as *type ! effect*, where both the type component and the effect component mention certain regions (for example, a type of a mutable memory cell is parameterized by the label of the memory region in which the cell resides).
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] The term "algebraic effect" follows from the type system.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] From a programmer's point of view, effects are useful as it allows for separating the implementation (*how*) of specific actions from the specification of what actions to perform.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] For example, an *ask name* effect can read from either the console, pop a window, or just return a default value.
[src:roc-language/algebraic-effect] The control flow can be described as a blend of *yield* (in that the execution continues) and *throw* (in that an unhandled effect propagates down until handled).
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM is written in C++ and is designed for compile-time, link-time, and runtime optimization.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The LLVM project started in 2000 at the University of Illinois Urbana–Champaign, under the direction of Vikram Adve and Chris Lattner.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM was originally developed as a research infrastructure to investigate dynamic compilation techniques for static and dynamic programming languages.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM was released under the University of Illinois/NCSA Open Source License, a permissive free software licence.
[src:roc-language/llvm] In 2005, Apple Inc. hired Lattner and formed a team to work on the LLVM system for various uses within Apple's development systems.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM has been an integral part of Apple's Xcode development tools for macOS and iOS since Xcode 4 in 2011.
[src:roc-language/llvm] In 2006, Lattner started working on a new project named Clang.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The combination of the Clang frontend and LLVM backend is named Clang/LLVM or simply Clang.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The name *LLVM* was originally an initialism for *Low Level Virtual Machine*.
[src:roc-language/llvm] However, the LLVM project evolved into an umbrella project that has little relationship to what most current developers think of as a virtual machine.
[src:roc-language/llvm] This made the initialism "confusing" and "inappropriate", and since 2011 LLVM is "officially no longer an acronym", but a brand that applies to the LLVM umbrella project.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The project encompasses the LLVM intermediate representation (IR), the LLVM debugger, the LLVM implementation of the C++ Standard Library (with full support of C++11 and C++14), etc.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM is administered by the LLVM Foundation.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Compiler engineer Tanya Lattner became its president in 2014 and was still president and Executive Director as of November 2025.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The project was originally available under the UIUC license.
[src:roc-language/llvm] After v9.0.0 released in 2019, LLVM relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:roc-language/llvm] As of November 2022 about 400 contributions had not been relicensed.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM can provide the middle layers of a complete compiler system, taking intermediate representation (IR) code from a compiler and emitting an optimized IR.
[src:roc-language/llvm] This new IR can then be converted and linked into machine-dependent assembly language code for a target platform.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM can accept the IR from the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) toolchain, allowing it to be used with a wide array of extant compiler front-ends written for that project.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM can also be built with gcc after version 7.5.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM can also generate relocatable machine code at compile-time or link-time or even binary machine code at runtime.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM supports a language-independent instruction set and type system.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Each instruction is in static single assignment form (SSA), meaning that each variable (called a typed register) is assigned once and then frozen.
[src:roc-language/llvm] This helps simplify the analysis of dependencies among variables.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM allows code to be compiled statically, as it is under the traditional GCC system, or left for late-compiling from the IR to machine code via just-in-time compilation (JIT), similar to Java.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The type system consists of basic types such as integer or floating-point numbers and five derived types: pointers, arrays, vectors, structures, and functions.
[src:roc-language/llvm] A type construct in a concrete language can be represented by combining these basic types in LLVM.
[src:roc-language/llvm] For example, a class in C++ can be represented by a mix of structures, functions and arrays of function pointers.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The LLVM JIT compiler can optimize unneeded static branches out of a program at runtime, and thus is useful for partial evaluation in cases where a program has many options, most of which can easily be determined unneeded in a specific environment.
[src:roc-language/llvm] This feature is used in the OpenGL pipeline of Mac OS X Leopard (v10.5) to provide support for missing hardware features.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Graphics code within the OpenGL stack can be left in intermediate representation and then compiled when run on the target machine.
[src:roc-language/llvm] On systems with high-end graphics processing units (GPUs), the resulting code remains quite thin, passing the instructions on to the GPU with minimal changes.
[src:roc-language/llvm] On systems with low-end GPUs, LLVM will compile optional procedures that run on the local central processing unit (CPU) that emulate instructions that the GPU cannot run internally.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM improved performance on low-end machines using Intel GMA chipsets.
[src:roc-language/llvm] A similar system was developed under the Gallium3D LLVMpipe, and incorporated into the GNOME shell to allow it to run without a proper 3D hardware driver loaded.
[src:roc-language/llvm] In 2011, programs compiled by GCC outperformed those from LLVM by 10%, on average.
[src:roc-language/llvm] In 2013, phoronix reported that LLVM had caught up with GCC, compiling binaries of approximately equal performance.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM has become an umbrella project containing multiple components.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM was originally written to be a replacement for the extant code generator in the GCC stack, and many of the GCC frontends were modified to work with it, resulting in the now-defunct LLVM-GCC suite.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The modifications generally involved a GIMPLE-to-LLVM IR step so that LLVM optimizers and codegen could be used instead of GCC's GIMPLE system.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Apple was a significant user of LLVM-GCC through Xcode 4.x (2013).
[src:roc-language/llvm] This use of the GCC frontend was considered a temporary measure; it became mostly obsolete with Apple's development of Clang, a newer compiler frontend, with a more modern, modular codebase and greater compilation speed, supporting C, C++, and Objective-C.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Support for LLVM-GCC was dropped in Xcode 5.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Primarily supported by Apple, Clang was aimed at replacing the C/Objective-C compiler in the GCC system with a system that is more easily integrated with integrated development environments (IDEs) and has wider support for multithreading.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Support for OpenMP directives has been included in Clang since release 3.8.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Widespread interest in LLVM has led to several efforts to develop new frontends for many other languages, including Ada, D, Delphi, Fortran, Haskell, Julia, Rust, Swift, and others.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The Utrecht Haskell compiler can generate code for LLVM.
[src:roc-language/llvm] While the generator was in early stages of development, in many cases it was more efficient than the C code generator.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) backend uses LLVM and achieves a 30% speed-up of compiled code relative to native code compiling via GHC or C code generation followed by compiling, missing only one of the many optimizing techniques implemented by the GHC.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Many other components are in various stages of development, including, but not limited to, a Java bytecode frontend, a Common Intermediate Language (CIL) frontend, the MacRuby implementation of Ruby 1.9, various frontends for Standard ML, and a new graph coloring register allocator.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The core of LLVM is the intermediate representation (IR), a low-level programming language similar to assembly.
[src:roc-language/llvm] IR is a strongly typed reduced instruction set computer (RISC) instruction set which abstracts away most details of the target.
[src:roc-language/llvm] For example, the calling convention is abstracted through `call` and `ret` instructions with explicit arguments.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Also, instead of a fixed set of registers, IR uses an infinite set of temporaries of the form %0, %1, etc.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM supports three equivalent forms of IR: a human-readable assembly format, an in-memory format suitable for frontends, and a dense bitcode format for serializing.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The many different conventions used and features provided by different targets mean that LLVM cannot truly produce a target-independent IR and retarget it without breaking some established rules.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Examples of target dependence beyond what is explicitly mentioned in the documentation can be found in a 2011 proposal for "wordcode", a fully target-independent variant of LLVM IR intended for online distribution.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The LLVM project also introduces another type of intermediate representation named MLIR which helps build reusable and extensible compiler infrastructure by employing a plugin architecture named Dialect.
[src:roc-language/llvm] It enables the use of higher-level information on the program structure in the process of optimization including polyhedral compilation.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Some features are not available on some platforms.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Most features are present for IA-32, x86-64, z/Architecture, ARM, and PowerPC.
[src:roc-language/llvm] In the past, LLVM also supported other backends, fully or partially, including C backend, Cell SPU, mblaze (MicroBlaze), AMD R600, DEC/Compaq Alpha (Alpha AXP) and Nios2, but that hardware is mostly obsolete, and LLVM developers decided the support and maintenance costs were no longer justified.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM also supports WebAssembly as a target, enabling compiled programs to execute in WebAssembly-enabled environments such as Google Chrome / Chromium, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari or WAVM.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM-compliant WebAssembly compilers typically support mostly unmodified source code written in C, C++, D, Rust, Nim, Kotlin and several other languages.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The LLVM machine code (MC) subproject is LLVM's framework for translating machine instructions between textual forms and machine code.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Formerly, LLVM relied on the system assembler, or one provided by a toolchain, to translate assembly into machine code.
[src:roc-language/llvm] LLVM MC's integrated assembler supports most LLVM targets, including IA-32, x86-64, ARM, and ARM64.
[src:roc-language/llvm] For some targets, including the various MIPS instruction sets, integrated assembly support is usable but still in the beta stage.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The lld subproject is an attempt to develop a built-in, platform-independent linker for LLVM. lld aims to remove dependence on a third-party linker.
[src:roc-language/llvm] As of May 2017, lld supports ELF, PE/COFF, Mach-O, and WebAssembly in descending order of completeness. lld is faster than both flavors of GNU ld.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Unlike the GNU linkers, lld has built-in support for link-time optimization (LTO).
[src:roc-language/llvm] This allows for faster code generation as it bypasses the use of a linker plugin, but on the other hand prohibits interoperability with other flavors of LTO.
[src:roc-language/llvm] The LLVM project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library named libc++, dual-licensed under the MIT License and the UIUC license.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Since v9.0.0, it was relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:roc-language/llvm] This implements a suite of cache-locality optimizations as well as auto-parallelism and vectorization using a polyhedral model.
[src:roc-language/llvm] llvm-libc is an incomplete, upcoming, ABI independent C standard library designed by and for the LLVM project.
[src:roc-language/llvm] Due to its permissive license, many vendors release their own tuned forks of LLVM.
[src:roc-language/llvm] This is officially recognized by LLVM's documentation, which suggests against using version numbers in feature checks for this reason.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In computer science, **pattern matching** is the act of checking a given sequence of tokens for the presence of the constituents of some pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In contrast to pattern recognition, the match usually must be exact: "either it will or will not be a match." The patterns generally have the form of either sequences or tree structures.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Uses of pattern matching include outputting the locations (if any) of a pattern within a token sequence, to output some component of the matched pattern, and to substitute the matching pattern with some other token sequence (i.e., search and replace).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Sequence patterns (e.g., a text string) are often described using regular expressions and matched using techniques such as backtracking.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Tree patterns are used in some programming languages as a general tool to process data based on its structure, e.g.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] C#, F#, Haskell, Java, ML, Python, Racket, Ruby, Rust, Scala, Swift and the symbolic mathematics language Mathematica have special syntax for expressing tree patterns and a language construct for conditional execution and value retrieval based on it.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Often it is possible to give alternative patterns that are tried one by one, which yields a powerful conditional programming construct.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Pattern matching sometimes includes support for guards.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Early programming languages with pattern matching constructs include COMIT (1957), SNOBOL (1962), which introduced pattern matching as a core, first-class language capability for string and text manipulation.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] This paradigm evolved into structured, tree-based data evaluation with Refal (1968), which used pattern matching to manipulate symbolic expressions.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The concept was soon adapted into logic programming with Prolog (1972), where pattern matching took the form of structural unification to resolve logical queries.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Functional programming languages rapidly adopted and formalized the feature across the late 1970s and early 1980s, beginning with the St Andrews Static Language (SASL) (1976), NPL (1977), and the Kent Recursive Calculator (KRC) (1981).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The pattern matching feature of function arguments in the language ML (1973) and its dialect Standard ML (1983) heavily formalized compile-time exhaustiveness checking.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] This approach has been carried over to some other functional programming languages that were influenced by them, such as Haskell (1990), Scala (2004), and F# (2005).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The pattern matching construct with the `match` keyword that was introduced in the ML dialect Caml (1985) was followed by languages such as OCaml (1996), F# (2005), F* (2011), and Rust (2015).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Over time, multi-paradigm languages begin implementing algebraic data types and pattern matching natively, culminating in modern implementations like Python's `match-case` syntax (2021) and Java's pattern matching enhancements (2023).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Many text editors support pattern matching of various kinds to facilitate advanced search-and-replace capabilities.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The QED editor, designed by Ken Thompson, was a pioneer in supporting regular expression searching.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Thompson's implementation of regular expression parsing in QED laid the groundwork for the text search utilities in ed, sed, and grep.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Furthermore, some versions of the TECO editor supported advanced matching features, including the logical OR operator in searches.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Computer algebra systems (CAS) generally support pattern matching on algebraic expressions to achieve symbolic simplification and integration.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Early systems like Macsyma (1968) used semantic pattern matching to recognize algebraic equivalence; for example, its internal engine could successfully match both `3x2 + 4` and `(x + 1)(x + 6)` as occurrences of a "quadratic in x" pattern template.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Modern computer algebra systems, including Mathematica and Maple, rely heavily on pattern-matching rules to transform user expressions, find analytical solutions to differential equations, and build user-defined simplification frameworks.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Pattern matching involves specialized terminology.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Pattern languages can be rich; see below for terminology denoting specific kinds of pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The value to be examined and matched against a pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Replacement of a portion of a scrutinee data structure with some computed value.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The computation may depend on the replaced portion of the scrutinee as well as on other bindings extracted from the scrutinee.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] While some concepts are relatively common to many pattern languages, other pattern languages include unique or unusual extensions.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] that portion when the continuation executes.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] , the wildcard pattern accepts all values without examining them further, ignoring their structure.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] is an expression that must succeed (or yield Boolean true) as a final step before considering a pattern to have successfully matched.
