[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The predicate is applied to the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the predicate in the pattern; if the predicate responds with Boolean false, the pattern is considered to have failed.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] to each element; the overall pattern thus succeeds only when the scrutinee is a list of even numbers.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] , where a user-defined function transforms the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the view pattern before continuing the match.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] View patterns generalize predicate patterns, allowing further matching on the result of the function rather than simply expecting a Boolean value.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Some pattern languages allow direct comparison of portions of the scrutinee with previously-computed (or constant) data structures.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Erlang, mention of any variable already in scope in a pattern causes it to act as a constraint in this way (instead of as a binding).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Some languages allow macros in pattern context to allow abstraction over patterns.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The simplest pattern in pattern matching is an explicit value or a variable.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Now, whenever f is given 0 as argument the pattern matches and the function returns 1.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] With any other argument, the matching and thus the function fail.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Here, the first `n` is a single variable pattern, which will match absolutely any argument and bind it to name n to be used in the rest of the definition.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell (unlike at least Hope), patterns are tried in order so the first definition still applies in the very specific case of the input being 0, while for any other argument the function returns `n * f (n-1)` with n being the argument.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The wildcard pattern (often written as `_`) is also simple: like a variable name, it matches any value, but does not bind the value to any name.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Algorithms for matching wildcards in simple string-matching situations have been developed in a number of recursive and non-recursive varieties.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] More complex patterns can be built from the primitive ones of the previous section, usually in the same way as values are built by combining other values.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The difference then is that with variable and wildcard parts, a pattern does not build into a single value, but matches a group of values that are the combination of the concrete elements and the elements that are allowed to vary within the structure of the pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] A tree pattern describes a part of a tree by starting with a node and specifying some branches and nodes and leaving some unspecified with a variable or wildcard pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] It may help to think of the abstract syntax tree of a programming language and algebraic data types.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell, the following line defines an algebraic data type `Color` that has a single data constructor `ColorConstructor` that wraps an integer and a string.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The constructor is a node in a tree and the integer and string are leaves in branches.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] When we want to write functions to make `Color` an abstract data type, we wish to write functions to interface with the data type, and thus we want to extract some data from the data type, for example, just the string or just the integer part of `Color`.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] If we pass a variable that is of type Color, how can we get the data out of this variable?
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The creations of these functions can be automated by Haskell's data record syntax.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] This OCaml example which defines a red–black tree and a function to re-balance it after element insertion shows how to match on a more complex structure generated by a recursive data type.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The compiler verifies at compile-time that the list of cases is exhaustive and none are redundant.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Pattern matching can be used to filter data of a certain structure.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, the only structure that exists is the tree, which is populated by symbols.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In the traditional, more suitable syntax, the symbols are written as they are and the levels of the tree are represented using `[]`, so that for instance `a[b,c]` is a tree with a as the parent, and b and c as the children.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] A pattern in Mathematica involves putting "_" at positions in that tree.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] will match elements such as A[1], A[2], or more generally A[*x*] where *x* is any entity.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In this case, `A` is the concrete element, while `_` denotes the piece of tree that can be varied.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] A symbol prepended to `_` binds the match to that variable name while a symbol appended to `_` restricts the matches to nodes of that symbol.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Note that even blanks themselves are internally represented as `Blank[]` for `_` and `Blank[x]` for `_x`.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Pattern matching applies to the *structure* of expressions.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] because only these elements will match the pattern `a[b[_],_]` above.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, it is also possible to extract structures as they are created in the course of computation, regardless of how or where they appear.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The function `Trace` can be used to monitor a computation, and return the elements that arise which match a pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Then, we can ask the question: Given fib[3], what is the sequence of recursive Fibonacci calls?
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In symbolic programming languages, it is easy to have patterns as arguments to functions or as elements of data structures.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] A consequence of this is the ability to use patterns to declaratively make statements about pieces of data and to flexibly instruct functions how to operate.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] For instance, the Mathematica function `Compile` can be used to make more efficient versions of the code.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The Curry–Howard correspondence between proofs and programs relates ML-style pattern matching to case analysis and proof by exhaustion.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] By far the most common form of pattern matching involves strings of characters.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In many programming languages, a particular syntax of strings is used to represent regular expressions, which are patterns describing string characters.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] However, it is possible to perform some string pattern matching within the same framework that has been discussed throughout this article.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, strings are represented as trees of root StringExpression and all the characters in order as children of the root.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Thus, to match "any amount of trailing characters", a new wildcard ___ is needed in contrast to _ that would match only a single character.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell and functional programming languages in general, strings are represented as functional lists of characters.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] A functional list is defined as an empty list, or an element constructed on an existing list.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The structure for a list with some elements is thus `element:list`.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] When pattern matching, we assert that a certain piece of data is equal to a certain pattern.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] We assert that the first element of `head`'s argument is called element, and the function returns this.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] We know that this is the first element because of the way lists are defined, a single element constructed onto a list.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The empty list would not match the pattern at all, as an empty list does not have a head (the first element that is constructed).
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] will match a string that has two characters and begins with "a".
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Symbolic entities can be introduced to represent many different classes of relevant features of a string.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] will match a string that consists of a letter first, and then a number.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The main advantage of symbolic string manipulation is that it can be completely integrated with the rest of the programming language, rather than being a separate, special purpose subunit.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] The entire power of the language can be leveraged to build up the patterns themselves or analyze and transform the programs that contain them.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:roc-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:roc-language/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In compiler design, **static single assignment form** (often abbreviated as **SSA form** or simply **SSA**) is a type of intermediate representation (IR) where each variable is assigned exactly once.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] SSA is used in most high-quality optimizing compilers for imperative languages, including LLVM, the GNU Compiler Collection, and many commercial compilers.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] There are efficient algorithms for converting programs into SSA form.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] To convert to SSA, existing variables in the original IR are split into versions, new variables typically indicated by the original name with a subscript, so that every definition gets its own version.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Additional statements that assign to new versions of variables may also need to be introduced at the join point of two control flow paths.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Converting from SSA form to machine code is also efficient.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] SSA makes numerous analyses needed for optimizations easier to perform, such as determining use-define chains, because when looking at a use of a variable there is only one place where that variable may have received a value.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Most optimizations can be adapted to preserve SSA form, so that one optimization can be performed after another with no additional analysis.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] The SSA based optimizations are usually more efficient and more powerful than their non-SSA form prior equivalents.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In functional language compilers, such as those for Scheme and ML, continuation-passing style (CPS) is generally used.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] SSA is formally equivalent to a well-behaved subset of CPS excluding non-local control flow, so optimizations and transformations formulated in terms of one generally apply to the other.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Using CPS as the intermediate representation is more natural for higher-order functions and interprocedural analysis.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] CPS also easily encodes call/cc, whereas SSA does not.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] SSA was developed in the 1980s by several researchers at IBM.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Kenneth Zadeck, a key member of the team, moved to Brown University as development continued.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A 1986 paper introduced birthpoints, identity assignments, and variable renaming such that variables had a single static assignment.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A subsequent 1987 paper by Jeanne Ferrante and Ronald Cytron proved that the renaming done in the previous paper removes all false dependencies for scalars.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Wegman, and Kenneth Zadeck replaced the identity assignments with Φ-functions, introduced the name "static single-assignment form", and demonstrated a now-common SSA optimization.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] The name Φ-function was chosen by Rosen to be a more publishable version of "phony function".
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Alpern, Wegman, and Zadeck presented another optimization, but using the name "static single assignment".
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Finally, in 1989, Rosen, Wegman, Zadeck, Cytron, and Ferrante found an efficient means of converting programs to SSA form.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] The primary usefulness of SSA comes from how it simultaneously simplifies and improves the results of a variety of compiler optimizations, by simplifying the properties of variables.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Humans can see that the first assignment is not necessary, and that the value of `y` being used in the third line comes from the second assignment of `y`.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A program would have to perform reaching definition analysis to determine this.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Converting ordinary code into SSA form is primarily a matter of replacing the target of each assignment with a new variable, and replacing each use of a variable with the "version" of the variable reaching that point.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Changing the name on the left hand side of "x $\leftarrow$ x - 3" and changing the following uses of *x* to that new name would leave the program unaltered.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] This can be exploited in SSA by creating two new variables: *x*1 and *x*2, each of which is assigned only once.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] It is clear which definition each use is referring to, except for one case: both uses of *y* in the bottom block could be referring to either *y*1 or *y*2, depending on which path the control flow took.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] To resolve this, a special statement is inserted in the last block, called a *Φ (Phi) function*.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] This statement will generate a new definition of *y* called *y*3 by "choosing" either *y*1 or *y*2, depending on the control flow in the past.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Now, the last block can simply use *y*3, and the correct value will be obtained either way.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A Φ function for *x* is not needed: only one version of *x*, namely *x*2 is reaching this place, so there is no problem (in other words, Φ(*x*2,*x*2)=*x*2).
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Given an arbitrary control-flow graph, it can be difficult to tell where to insert Φ functions, and for which variables.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] This general question has an efficient solution that can be computed using a concept called *dominance frontiers* (see below).
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Φ functions are not implemented as machine operations on most machines.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A compiler can implement a Φ function by inserting "move" operations at the end of every predecessor block.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In the example above, the compiler might insert a move from *y*1 to *y*3 at the end of the middle-left block and a move from *y*2 to *y*3 at the end of the middle-right block.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] These move operations might not end up in the final code based on the compiler's register allocation procedure.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] However, this approach may not work when simultaneous operations are speculatively producing inputs to a Φ function, as can happen on wide-issue machines.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Typically, a wide-issue machine has a selection instruction used in such situations by the compiler to implement the Φ function.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In a control-flow graph, a node A is said to **strictly dominate** a different node B if it is impossible to reach B without passing through A first.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In other words, if node B is reached, then it can be assumed that A has run.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A is said to *dominate* B (or B to *be dominated by* A) if either A strictly dominates B or A = B.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A node which transfers control to a node A is called an **immediate predecessor** of A.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] The **dominance frontier** of node A is the set of nodes B where A *does not* strictly dominate B, but does dominate some immediate predecessor of B.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] These are the points at which multiple control paths merge back together into a single path.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Node 1 strictly dominates 2, 3, and 4 and the immediate predecessors of node 4 are nodes 2 and 3.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Dominance frontiers define the points at which Φ functions are needed.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In the above example, when control is passed to node 4, the definition of `result` used depends on whether control was passed from node 2 or 3. Φ functions are not needed for variables defined in a dominator, as there is only one possible definition that can apply.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] There is an efficient algorithm for finding dominance frontiers of each node.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] This algorithm was originally described in "Efficiently Computing Static Single Assignment Form and the Control Graph" by Ron Cytron, Jeanne Ferrante, et al. in 1991.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In the code above, `idom(b)` is the **immediate dominator** of b, the unique node that strictly dominates b but does not strictly dominate any other node that strictly dominates b.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] "Minimal" SSA inserts the minimal number of Φ functions required to ensure that each name is assigned a value exactly once and that each reference (use) of a name in the original program can still refer to a unique name.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] However, some of these Φ functions could be *dead*.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] For this reason, minimal SSA does not necessarily produce the fewest Φ functions that are needed by a specific procedure.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] For some types of analysis, these Φ functions are superfluous and can cause the analysis to run less efficiently.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Pruned SSA form is based on a simple observation: Φ functions are only needed for variables that are "live" after the Φ function.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] (Here, "live" means that the value is used along some path that begins at the Φ function in question.) If a variable is not live, the result of the Φ function cannot be used and the assignment by the Φ function is dead.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Construction of pruned SSA form uses live-variable information in the Φ function insertion phase to decide whether a given Φ function is needed.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] If the original variable name isn't live at the Φ function insertion point, the Φ function isn't inserted.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Another possibility is to treat pruning as a dead-code elimination problem.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Then, a Φ function is live only if any use in the input program will be rewritten to it, or if it will be used as an argument in another Φ function.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] When entering SSA form, each use is rewritten to the nearest definition that dominates it.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] A Φ function will then be considered live as long as it is the nearest definition that dominates at least one use, or at least one argument of a live Φ.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Semi-pruned SSA form is an attempt to reduce the number of Φ functions without incurring the relatively high cost of computing live-variable information.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] It is based on the following observation: if a variable is never live upon entry into a basic block, it never needs a Φ function.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] During SSA construction, Φ functions for any "block-local" variables are omitted.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Computing the set of block-local variables is a simpler and faster procedure than full live-variable analysis, making semi-pruned SSA form more efficient to compute than pruned SSA form.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] On the other hand, semi-pruned SSA form will contain more Φ functions.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Block arguments are an alternative to Φ functions that is representationally identical but in practice can be more convenient during optimization.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Blocks are named and take a list of block arguments, notated as function parameters.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] When calling a block the block arguments are bound to specified values.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] MLton, Swift SIL, and MLIR use block arguments.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Block arguments make the connection to continuation-passing style (CPS) more apparent: basic blocks are functions, function variables are block arguments (Φ functions).
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] SSA form is not normally used for direct execution (although it is possible to interpret SSA), and it is frequently used "on top of" another IR with which it remains in direct correspondence.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] This can be accomplished by "constructing" SSA as a set of functions that map between parts of the existing IR (basic blocks, instructions, operands, *etc.*) and its SSA counterpart.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] When the SSA form is no longer needed, these mapping functions may be discarded, leaving only the now-optimized IR.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Performing optimizations on SSA form usually leads to entangled SSA-Webs, meaning there are Φ instructions whose operands do not all have the same root operand.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] In such cases color-out algorithms are used to come out of SSA.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Naive algorithms introduce a copy along each predecessor path that caused a source of different root symbol to be put in Φ than the destination of Φ.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] There are multiple algorithms for coming out of SSA with fewer copies, most use interference graphs or some approximation of it to do copy coalescing.
[src:roc-language/static-single-assignment-form] Extensions to SSA form can be divided into two categories.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:roc-language/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:roc-language/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:roc-language/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:roc-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
